    "notes": "Cost-blind ordering: a model with only names/descriptions/prices anchors on the lowest menu prices and generic 'cheap pasta = bang for buck' priors, so it picks Cacio e Pepe ($31, the cheapest-feeling entree) or a $14-15 side/salad as 'best value' -- which is actually the WORST value at ~11x markup. The true best value is the Jumbo Lump Crab Cakes at 2.16x: it looks like a $34 ripoff starter, but jumbo lump crab is so expensive wholesale ($2.55/oz x 6oz) that the markup is the lowest on the menu. Bone-in Prime Ribeye (2.29x) is a close second -- a 28oz Prime cut at $1.05/oz raw delivers enormous food-per-dollar. Hidden gem: Lobster Mac (2.46x), a humble-sounding pasta carried by real lobster. Prestige trap: Filet Mignon at $60 looks like THE indulgence but runs 5.63x markup -- markedly WORSE value than the cheaper-per-ounce, larger Bone-in Ribeye (2.29x); the priciest-feeling steak is not the best deal. Markup ordering (low=best): Crab Cakes 2.16, Bone-in Ribeye 2.29, Lobster Mac 2.46, Shrimp Creole 3.85, Gumbo 3.89, NY Strip 4.03, Bread Pudding 4.13, Creamed Spinach 4.58, Hal's Wedge 4.84, Branzino 5.13, Truffle Fries 5.26, Filet Mignon 5.63, Old Fashioned 6.05, Caesar 6.61, Espresso Martini 6.67, Cacio e Pepe 10.97. Cocktails and simple sides/pasta carry the fattest markups; expensive raw proteins are the diner's best ROI."
